Citation.sTitle: Solubility of C02 in dialkylimidazolium dialkylphosphate ionic liquids
Citation.sAbstract: The solubility of carbon dioxide in room temperature ionic liquids (RTILs), dialkylimidazolium  dialkylphosphates, was measured at 313-333 K and at pressures close to atmospheric pressure,  from which Henry's law coefficients, standard Gibbs free energy, enthalpy, and entropy changes of  solvation were derived. The C02 solubility in the dialkylimidazolium dialkylphosphate was found  to increase with increasing chain length of the alkyl groups on the cation and/or the anion as  was similarly found in other RTILs. Among various dialkylimidazolium dialkylphosphates tested,  l-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium diethylphosphate ([EMIM][Et2P04)) and l-butyl-3-methylimidazolium  dibutylphosphate ([BMIM][Bu2P04)) exhibited the comparable or better capability of dissolving C02  in comparison with that of [BMIM][BF4J, but their absorption capacities were still lower than that of  l-butyl-3-methylimidazolium bis(trifluoromethylsulfonyl)imide ([BMIMJ[Tf2N)).
